he mothers in each poem are portrayed T
quite differently. In Harrison’s poem,
the narrator’s mother seems strong and
courageous. The “steady” clicking of
her knitting needles shows she was
undisturbed by the sound of bombs
outside and symbolises the steadying
inuence she had on the narrator. This
contrasts with the “anguish” of the
mother in ‘Handbag’. This anguish is
mentioned in the summary of the bag’s
“Odour”, which implies that it is part
of the narrator’s lasting impression of
their mother. It suggests that the torment
caused by the loss of the narrator’s father
was a large aspect of the mother’s life.
 Both poems use the senses to convey
the narrators’ vivid memories about
items associated with their mothers. In
‘Handbag’, the poet describes the very
specic smell of the handbag — of
“mints / and lipstick and Coty powder”.
This emphasises how familiar the narrator
is with the handbag, because they can
recall exactly how it smells. In ‘Jumper’,
the poet uses the onomatopoeia of the
word “click” to clearly convey the sound
of the mother’s knitting needles. This
helps the reader to imagine what the
narrator could hear and understand the
calming effect that it had on them.
 The poems both use repetition. In
‘Handbag’, repetition of the word
“letters” emphasises how important
the “Letters from my father” were to
the narrator’s mother, and how they
dominate the narrator’s memories of her.
Similarly, in ‘Jumper’, the word “bombs”
is repeated at random points, echoing the
random explosions of bombs during the
war. This helps the reader to understand
the danger the family faced and the
mother’s courage in facing it so “calmly”.
T
he two poems use rhyme and rhythm in
different ways. The use of enjambment
in ‘Handbag’ gives the poem a slow
rhythm, which seems wistful and
melancholy, while the lack of rhyme
makes the poem seem natural and
personal. This reects the narrator’s own
sadness when they look back on their
mother’s life and her suffering during the
war. In contrast, in ‘Jumper’, the regular
rhyme scheme creates an even rhythm,
which mirrors the sound of the mother’s
knitting needles. This emphasises the
narrator’s admiration for the calm way
their mother carried on knitting as
“German bombs fell”.
he tone in ‘Handbag’ remains wistful
T
and nostalgic throughout — the narrator
describes the “smell” of their mother’s
handbag at the beginning of the poem
and also at the end, when they refer to
“Odour / of leather and powder”. This
shows how the narrator is continuing to
reect on their memories of their mother.
In contrast, the separation of the nal
line in ‘Jumper’ signals a change in tone
as well as a jump in time from past to
present. This abrupt end to the poem
mirrors the narrator’s shock when they
opened the present.

Warm-up Questions
1)he poem is about a woman who is T
left behind in her home, waiting for
someone she lives with to return.
2) The main feeling of the rst stanza is
boredom. The poet portrays this by
describing how the woman has “nothing
to do” and so she just “dusts the house”
and “sweeps the bleached verandah”.
The woman’s cleaning also shows she
feels anxious — she cannot sit still and
tries to keep busy. But the cleaning is
futile; the broom “leaves a trail of grit”.
This could show that she can’t cleanse
her mind of her fear and anxiety.
3) The coat that the woman uses for
a pillow could be the man’s coat.
Sleeping with it could help the woman
to feel closer to him, and help her to feel
reassured that he will return to her. She
may also be waiting up for the man, so
might be reluctant to go to bed properly.
4) The word “loathed” expresses the
woman’s fear and hatred of the sea
— in her nightmare, it is invading her
house like a dangerous enemy. The
ocean is the reason she is separated
from the man, and it presents a danger
to him, so she may loathe the ocean
because it is the cause of her misery.
5)In the second stanza, the ocean is
personied as entering the woman’s
home by “climbing the cliffs, / creeping
in through the door”. This makes the
sea seem hostile, as if it is creeping
up on her to steal away the man she
is waiting for. The personication
suggests that the woman feels
threatened by the ocean, and reects
how powerless the sea makes her feel.
6) By the end of the poem, the woman’s
feelings of unease have intensied. In
the last two lines, the woman feels
the “high tide’s breakers’ / chill in her
arms”. This cold, wet image creates a
negative mood that reects the woman’s
fear and unhappiness, and suggests
the “loathed ocean” has taken over
her home as she feared. The “chill” of
the waves seems like a forewarning of
death. It’s as if she’s holding the man’s
drowned body, which emphasises the
sense of unease in this part of the poem.
he rhythm throughout the poem
is erratic, with no rhyme scheme,
reecting the woman’s anxious state of
mind and her urge to keep doing things
to keep busy. The nal stanza is heavily
enjambed, which creates a feeling of
time moving faster and of disorder and
confusion, emphasising the woman’s
deteriorating state of mind as a feeling
of dread sweeps over her.
The structure of the poem mimics the
structure of the woman’s life while the
man is away — it’s divided into day,
night, day, across the three stanzas. This
lets the reader follow her experience
over this time and understand her
feelings of monotony and fear.
9) The title ‘At Sea’ suggests that the
absent man may be out at sea in a boat,
and emphasises how much the woman
is thinking about him. It may also refer
to how the woman feels ‘at sea’ (lost
and alone) without him, emphasising
her strong sense of his absence.
Focus on... Sound
1) a) The phrase “she dusts the house”
uses sibilance.
b) The repeated ‘s’ sounds make the
line feel longer, reecting the woman’s
feelings about how time slows down
whilst she’s alone. The sibilance also
sounds like the sea, so it’s a constant
reminder of the woman’s enemy.
2) a) The phrase “climbing the cliffs”
uses alliteration.
b) The repetition of the hard ‘c’
sound makes the sea sound threatening.
This emphasises the woman’s fear.
3) In the nal stanza, the onomatopoeic
sound of the “screaming” gulls creates
a vivid image for the reader and gives
a nightmarish quality to the poem. It’s
also a stark contrast to the silence of
the rest of the poem, where the only
sounds are the sweeping of the broom
and the sibilance of the sea creeping
closer. The screaming gulls are also
reminiscent of the screams of drowning
sailors, highlighting the woman’s fear
that the man she awaits will die at sea.

Warm-up Questions
1) The poem is about the sea and its
behaviour at different times of the day
and the year, including when it is rough
and when it is calm.
2) a) The metaphor likens the power
and energy of the sea to the hunger
and enthusiasm of a dog, by describing
how the ‘dog’ “gnaws” on stones and
“bounds to his feet”. It also shows how
the sea can sometimes be calm and
quiet, like a sleeping dog.
b) The metaphor is effective because
it shows the changeable nature of the
sea through a dog’s personality and
behaviour at different times.
3) The ‘dog’ gnawing at the “rumbling,
tumbling stones” represents the sea
moving the stones on the beach as it
moves in and out. The ‘dog’s’ gnawing
helps the reader imagine the sound of
the stones as they rub and grind against
each other. It may also suggest the
gradual erosion of the stones into sand
due to the effect of the sea.
